:: Modern Monetary Theory Side Quest {"position":"750,225","size":"100,100"}
Money's origin isn't rooted in widespread barter as commonly believed. Societies historically pooled resources, with people contributing based on ability and receiving based on needs. 

Money emerged to incentivise larger and less well-acquainted groups of people to do things - for example, when kings sent their armies on long campaigns, rather than having to bring all their supplies with them, they imposed taxes on the people living in the land through which they passed. 

To earn the money to pay those taxes, the people could give some of their food to the passing armies, or give them accommodation for the night.

In other words, the state uses its power to impose a tax on the people living in it, thereby creating unemployment and requiring people to work to pay that tax. And in order for the people to be able to earn the currency the state has to create it in the first place - so it must spend money into the economy (i.e. by giving the money to its armies to give to the people who provide them with food and shelter) before it can collect it back in tax.

And if the state spends more than it taxes back (what‚Äôs known as a deficit ‚Äî the opposite would be a surplus), this allows people to save, or to exchange that money with other people for goods and services - in other words, a state deficit is a good thing for us. The only risk comes if the state puts too much money into an area where there‚Äôs already a lot of competition for resources - this is what might lead to inflation (which you‚Äôll learn more about in the game).

One other important thing is that this only works if you have monetary sovereignty - that is you don‚Äôt have a fixed exchange rate to any other currency or commodity, and you have little to no debt in foreign currencies. This is not the case for many Global South countries, so we should be fighting to cancel their foreign debts and help them achieve this.

This is definitely not the only way to run an economy - perhaps in an ideal world, we wouldn‚Äôt need money at all. But for now it‚Äôs what we have, so it‚Äôs important to know the rules and make sure everyone can thrive in this system.

