:: find out more about where the inflation is coming from {"position":"450,750","size":"100,100"}
This is the right call! There‚Äôs two main kinds of inflation - cost push and demand pull. The methods to fight these are different.

For demand pull, this is the traditional "too much money chasing too few goods and services" situation that economists traditionally try to cool with interest rate hikes. This rarely happens, but if it does, then a more targeted approach would be to try to reduce demand on the sector causing the increase (e.g. if it's petrol prices, make public transport free or low cost). 

For cost push, interest rate hikes don't work at all. You have to target the actual issues causing the costs to increase - for example, when the economy picked up again a few months into the Covid pandemic, there were bottlenecks in the supply chain where ports weren't processing containers quickly enough because they were making so much money having increased prices for each container so much. The US imposed a tax for containers sitting empty on the docks, which caused them to increase the rate of processing again, and improved supply of goods to the economy.

So let's find out more about the [[source of the inflation]]


